<AbstractNarration>0095057/Curry&lt;br/&gt;&lt;br/&gt;In the late 1980s and early 1990s the source of Labrador Sea Water (LSW) &lt;br/&gt;became colder, fresher and denser during a persistent high phase of the &lt;br/&gt;North Atlantic Oscillation.  This provided an anomalous signature which &lt;br/&gt;could be used to track deep water as it flows south in the Deep Western &lt;br/&gt;Boundary Current (DWBC) of the North Atlantic.  This project will &lt;br/&gt;analyze data collected from a series of sections across the deep western &lt;br/&gt;boundary current in and near the tropical Atlantic, including some that &lt;br/&gt;were recently made under a Small Grant for Exploratory Research.  One &lt;br/&gt;aim is to determine the speed with which the anomalous LSW signal is &lt;br/&gt;traveling along the western boundary of the North Atlantic.  This will &lt;br/&gt;provide an estimate of how rapidly climate signals associated with &lt;br/&gt;adjustments in the ocean's meridional overturning circulation can &lt;br/&gt;propagate from high to low latitudes.  This is an important parameter &lt;br/&gt;in many scenarios of climate change and one that can be used to test &lt;br/&gt;the fidelity of climate models.  A second aim is to determine the &lt;br/&gt;dynamical effects on the DWBC of the passage of this anomalously low &lt;br/&gt;potential vorticity.&lt;br/&gt;</AbstractNarration>
